Not less than 45 front and back shops have been destroyed in Kaduna as fire razed down a food market within the metropolis. The incident took place at Birni Kudu market in the Bakin Dogo area close to the Kaduna Central Market. The incident was said to have started about 2 am in the early hours of Wednesday morning. The affected traders who said they have lost millions in the inferno are now appealing to the Kaduna State government and other wealthy individuals to come to their rescue. The shops were said to have been built in the 70s, were mainly used for the sale and stocking of assorted foodstuffs like yam flour, cassava flour, guinea corn and beans, rice other grains. Hajiya Aisha a trader in the market said her family lost four shops in the inferno, saying “the whole thing happened so fast. It was one of the guards that called us this morning to inform us of this unfortunate incident. “We are appealing to the state government and other spirited individuals to come to our aid. We have lost everything we had worked for to this fire. All we need now is help. However, when contacted, Director, Kaduna State Fire Services, Paul Fidelis Aboi, said, his team of firefighter responded to the distress call within two minutes. “The fire may have started by 2 am as they claimed, but we responded within two minutes the information got to us and we have already surpassed it from escalating into other areas. “As at now, we are still investigating the immediate cause of the fire. But the season we are, that is hammatan, is partly responsible for fire outbreak. We rely on 100 percent on an emergency call or people running to our office to lay complaints,” he said.